  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN199.1-kilavi">poruḷkaṭaikkūṭṭiya neñciṟkut talaimakaṉ colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What HE said to [his] heart that had secured wealth.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN199.1">
        <l><anchor n="1"/>karaipāy veṇṭirai kaṭuppap palavuṭa</l>
        <l>ṉiraikā loṟṟaliṟ kalcēr putirum</l>
        <l>varaicēr marāat tūḻalar peyalcet</l>
        <l>tuyaṅkayal yāṉai nīrnacaik kalamarac</l>
        <l>cilampi valanta vaṟuñciṉai vaṟṟa</l>
        <l>valaṅka lulavai yariniḻa lacaiit</l>
        <l>tāṅkumaraṟ kavviya kaiyaṟu tokunilai</l>
        <l>ya<supplied>ra</supplied>n<supplied>ti</supplied> ṉūcit tiraṇuti yaṉṉa</l>
        <l>tiṇṇilai yeyiṟṟa<anchor n="2"/> cennā yeṭuttaliṉ</l>
        <l>vaḷimuṉaip pūḷaiyi ṉoyyeṉa valaṟiya</l>
        <l>kāṭumā ṉiṉanirai tēriya kalaiyē</l>
        <l>katirmāy mālai yāṇkural viḷikkuṅ</l>
        <l>kaṭalpōl kāṉam piṉpaṭap piṟarpōṟ</l>
        <l>celvē māyiṉeñ celavunaṉ ṟeṉṉu</l>
        <l>mācai yuḷḷa macaiviṉṟu turappa</l>
        <l>nīcelaṟ kuriyai neñcē vēypōṟ</l>
        <l>ṟaṭaiyiṉa maṉṉun taṇṇiya tiraṇṭa</l>
        <l>peruntō ḷarivai yoḻiyak kuṭāa</l>
        <l>tirumpoṉ vākaip peruntuṟaic ceruviṟ</l>
        <l>polampū ṇaṉṉaṉ porukaḷat toḻiya</l>
        <l>valampaṭu koṟṟan tanta vāyvāṭ</l>
        <l>kaḷaṅkāy kaṇṇi nāṇmuṭic cēra</l>
        <l>liḻanta nāṭutan taṉṉa</l>
        <l>vaḷamperitu peṟiṉum vārale ṉiyāṉē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>You have the right to go, heart, (16a-c)</l>
        <l>as restlessly [your] eager mind urges [you] (15)</l>
        <l>that says “our going will be good if we go, (14)</l>
        <l>like others, so that the forest [large] as the sea lies behind [us], (13)</l>
        <l>where, while the weakening nearby elephant turns about out of longing for water, (4)</l>
        <l>thinking the aged blossoms of the Kadamba tree next to the mountain [to be] rain, (3)</l>
        <l>that drop off, joining the stones because of the wind pressing on [their] rows, (2)</l>
        <l>many together, so that they resemble white waves spreading on the shore, (1)</l>
        <l>a male voice calls out through the evening when the [sun] rays vanish: (12)</l>
        <l>the stag, as it searches for [its] herd of deer in the wilderness (11)</l>
        <l>that cry out urgently, like wool plants on the wind[-blown] frontier, (10)</l>
        <l>because the red dog startles [them], its teeth in a state as firm (9)</l>
        <l>as the round tips of needles eaten by the file, (8)</l>
        <l>in a collective state of desolation when they seize the durable bowstring hemp (7)</l>
        <l>after resting in the cut shade of the swaying dry branches (6)</l>
        <l>when the poor twigs dry up that are encircled by spider [webs]. (5)</l>
        <l>Even if [I] were to gain great prosperity, (24ab)</l>
        <l>like that brought from the land that had been lost (23)</l>
        <l>by the Cēra with a day[-fresh] crown [and] a chaplet, Kalaṅkāy, (22)</l>
        <l>with a superb sword that brought [him] a triumphant victory (21)</l>
        <l>so that Naṉṉaṉ with golden ornaments stayed behind on the battlefield (20)</l>
        <l>in a fight by the big harbour of great golden Vākai in the west, (18df.)</l>
	      <l rend="indent8">I won’t come, (24cd)</l>
        <l>so that [my] girl with wide shoulders stays behind, (18a-c)</l>
        <l>that are rounded [and] cool which remain curved like bamboo. (16df.)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
